## Immutable principles

### 1. {{PRINCIPLE_NAME}}
{{DESCRIPTION}}

**Why:** {{REASON}}

### 2. Security by layers (defense in depth)
Never rely on a single validation layer. Each request passes through:
- Local validation (no cost)
- Lightweight AI check if needed (Haiku, ~$0.001)
- Full analysis only if previous layers pass (Sonnet, ~$0.025)

**Why:** An attacker who bypasses one layer still faces the others. Also reduces API cost by filtering early.

### 3. Fail explicitly
When detecting an error or invalid input:
- Explain exactly WHAT was detected
- Return a structured error code
- Do NOT approve doubtful cases "just in case"

**Why:** A false negative (approving bad input) is far more damaging than a false positive.

### 4. API cost proportional to risk
The most expensive model only runs if input passed all cheap validations.

**Why:** Allows scaling without cost growing linearly with bad input volume.

### 5. Spec-driven architecture
Every module has its spec in `specs/`. Every architecture decision has its ADR in `docs/plan/`. Code implements specs, not the other way around.

**Why:** When the team grows or a new developer joins, decisions are already documented.

### 6. Idempotency in webhooks
All payment webhooks must check if the event was already processed before crediting. A webhook can arrive more than once.

**Why:** Payment providers retry failed webhooks. Without idempotency check, a user could receive double credits.

